# Predictive Paradox — IITG.ai Recruitment Task

my submission for the IITG.ai recruitment task. the problem was to forecast the next hour's electricity demand on Bangladesh's national grid using only classical ML — no LSTMs, no ARIMA, nothing like that. just tabular features and a tree-based model.

---

## repo structure

```
PredictiveParadox_Aadisankar.ipynb   # the full pipeline
images/
    feature_importance.png           # generated when you run the notebook
README.md
```

the three dataset files (PGCB_date_power_demand.xlsx, weather_data.xlsx, economic_full_1.csv) aren't in the repo — too large. mount them from Google Drive as shown at the top of the notebook.

---

## how to run

1. put the three dataset files in your Google Drive
2. open the notebook in Colab
3. run `drive.mount('/content/drive')` and fix the file paths in Part 1 if they don't match your Drive structure
4. run all cells in order

numpy, pandas, matplotlib, seaborn, scikit-learn, xgboost are all standard Colab libraries. optuna gets pip installed inline in the notebook.

---

## what i did

### data cleaning

the raw PGCB data was messy — duplicate timestamps, missing generation columns for sources that didn't exist yet (solar, wind, imports from India/Nepal), and some really suspicious demand spikes.

- solar/wind/import columns with NaNs → filled with 0. not interpolated because these weren't just missing readings, they genuinely weren't generating power in those years
- fully duplicate rows → dropped. timestamps with two slightly different readings → averaged into one
- outliers → rolling Z-score over a 7-day window, threshold 3.2. i went with 3.2 rather than the more common 2.5 because being too aggressive would clip real demand peaks, which are exactly what the model needs to learn
- any post-2022 rows showing demand under 4000 MW → dropped, that's physically impossible for a grid this size

### data integration

the economic data (World Bank annual indicators — GDP, population, electricity access, energy use, industry output) came as a wide CSV. melted it to long format, pivoted by year, then merged onto the hourly series by matching calendar year. gaps between years filled with linear interpolation.

weather data was already hourly, just needed to be rounded to the hour and merged on datetime. small gaps (≤3 consecutive hours) filled with time-based interpolation.

### feature engineering

since tree-based models have no built-in sense of time, i had to manually give the model a "memory" of the past. here's what i ended up with:

**calendar stuff** — hour, day of week, day of month, month, quarter, is_weekend, is_friday, week of year

**cyclical encoding** — sin/cos for hour, month, day-of-week. this matters because without it the model thinks hour 23 and hour 0 are far apart when they're actually adjacent

**lag features** — lag_1h, 2h, 3h, 6h, 12h, 24h, 48h, 72h, 168h, and a lag_1month (same hour, one month ago). the 24h and 168h lags are the most useful for capturing daily and weekly patterns

**rolling features** — rolling mean and std over 3h, 6h, 12h, 24h, 168h windows. critically, all of these are computed with `shift(1)` before the rolling window — this is how i avoided data leakage, every row only sees what was available *before* that hour

**target-hour features** — calendar features for the hour being *predicted* (t+1), not the current hour. helps the model know what time it's forecasting into

**interaction features** — heat_stress (temp × humidity), extreme_heat flag, solar_efficiency, renewable_share, import_share, fossil_load, evening_heat_stress, weekend_heat. also `actual_need_estimate` = demand + load_shedding, which corrects for the fact that recorded demand is artificially suppressed during load shedding events

**target** — demand_mw shifted back by 1 row (next hour's demand)

### train / test split

everything before 2023-01-01 → training. 2023 onwards → hold-out test. no shuffling.

one thing that tripped me up early: i initially split at 2022 and the model couldn't predict above ~14k MW. turned out demand above 14k only starts appearing from mid-2022, so those values were entirely absent from training. moving the cutoff to 2023 fixed it — tree models literally cannot predict outside the range they were trained on.

### modeling

ran three baselines first (GradientBoostingRegressor, XGBoostRegressor, RandomForestRegressor with default params) to see which was worth tuning. XGBoost came out ahead.

tuned with Optuna — 15 trials, minimising MAE on a chronological 80/20 split within the training data. params tuned: n_estimators, learning_rate, max_depth, min_child_weight, subsample, colsample_bytree.

final model adds reg_alpha=0.1 and reg_lambda=1.5 on top of the best Optuna params. also used sample weights to stop the model from ignoring high-demand rows: 1.5× above 9000 MW, 2.5× above 11000 MW, 4× above 13000 MW.

---

## results

| metric | value |
|---|---|
| MAPE — full 2023 test set | 2.64% |
| MAPE — >13000 MW subset only | 4.04% |

2.64% on a full unseen year felt pretty good. the higher MAPE on the extreme demand region makes sense — those hours are rare in training even with sample weighting.

---

## feature importance

plotted two views side by side — permutation importance and XGBoost's native gain importance. permutation importance is generally more trustworthy because it measures how much prediction quality actually drops when you shuffle a feature, rather than just counting how many splits used it (which inflates continuous features like lag_1h).

![Feature Importance](images/feature_importance.png)

top drivers ended up being lag_1h, rolling demand means at various windows, temperature, and hour-of-day. the economic features matter less individually but they anchor the long-run upward trend across years that lag features can't fully capture on their own.
